## User

Yes. You can build that with pure Three.js particles, no shader needed.
And yes, we can use the same ideology you already learned.
The effect:
JPEG image
→ crack appears
→ image bursts into particles
→ particles spread across page and float
→ after a few seconds particles return
→ image reforms
→ repeat
This can be done with:
Canvas image sampling
BufferGeometry particles
start positions
burst positions
animation progress
state machine
No shader required.
Core Mental Model
Same as your text particles:
Each particle has:
  home position = where it belongs in the image
  burst position = where it flies during explosion
Then one animation value controls:
0 = image formed
1 = image exploded
Use lerp():
particle position = lerp(homePosition, burstPosition, explodeAmount)
That’s the whole heart of it.
Workflow
Load JPEG texture/image.

Draw the image onto a hidden 2D canvas.

Sample pixels from the canvas.

For each sampled pixel:
create one particle
store image/home position
store pixel color
store random burst position

Create THREE.Points.

In animation loop:
formed state: particles sit in image shape
cracking state: maybe shake or split along crack line
burst state: particles fly outward
floating state: particles drift slowly
return state: particles lerp back home
repeat

Important Data Arrays
You will need arrays like:
positions
homePositions
burstPositions
colors
randomSeeds
Meaning:
positions:
  current particle positions used by Three.js

homePositions:
  where particles form the image

burstPositions:
  where particles go when exploded

colors:
  color copied from JPEG pixel

randomSeeds:
  unique random values for floating/wobble
State Machine
This is the big concept.
Instead of one hover boolean, this animation repeats automatically.
Use states:
FORMED
CRACKING
BURSTING
FLOATING
RETURNING
Noob meaning:
FORMED:
  image is normal

CRACKING:
  particles around crack shift slightly

BURSTING:
  particles move toward burst positions

FLOATING:
  particles hover around spread positions

RETURNING:
  particles move back to image positions
Then repeat.
Timing Example
0s - 1s:
  image formed

1s - 2s:
  crack appears / shake begins

2s - 3.5s:
  burst outward

3.5s - 5s:
  particles float

5s - 6.5s:
  return to image

6.5s:
  repeat
Crack Without Shader
Since no shader, the crack can be faked using particles.
You can do:
define a jagged crack line through the image
For each particle, check:
is this particle near the crack line?
If yes:
push it slightly left/right/up/down
make it brighter/white
shake it
That creates the illusion of a crack.
No need to actually draw a crack texture.
Crack Concept
Create a jagged line:
start near top
go downward with random x offsets
Then for each particle:
find how close particle is to crack line
if close:
  crackInfluence = strong
else:
  crackInfluence = weak/zero
During cracking phase:
particle position += crackDirection * crackInfluence
This makes a split.
Burst Concept
For every particle, create a burst target:
burstX = homeX + random direction * random distance
burstY = homeY + random direction * random distance
burstZ = homeZ + random depth
For page-wide spread:
burstX across viewport width
burstY across viewport height
burstZ closer/farther
If you want dramatic burst:
particles near crack move first
particles far from crack move later
That makes the crack feel like it causes the explosion.
Floating Concept
After burst, do not freeze particles.
Use sine/cosine with seeds:
particleX = burstX + sin(time + seed) * smallAmount
particleY = burstY + cos(time + seed) * smallAmount
Noob meaning:
Each particle gently floats differently.
Return Concept
After floating:
particle position = lerp(current/burst position, home position, returnProgress)
Then reset to formed.
Where To Put It In Three.js
You can make this as a new group:
imageParticleGroup
Or a new THREE.Points.
It can be:
in world space
or:
attached to camera
If you want it to spread across the webpage/screen, camera-attached is easier.
Like:
camera.add(imageParticles)
Then positions are screen-like.
What You Should Build First
Do not start with crack.
Build in this order:
Make particles form the JPEG image.
Make them explode outward.
Make them return.
Add repeat timing.
Add floating motion.
Add crack influence.
Add particle colors from image.
That order matters. Crack is the fancy part. Get the image-particle loop working first.
Pseudocode
load jpeg image

draw image to hidden canvas

for every N pixels:
  read pixel color

  create particle

  homePosition:
    x = pixel x mapped to Three.js width
    y = pixel y mapped to Three.js height
    z = 0

  burstPosition:
    x = random across screen
    y = random across screen
    z = random depth

  color:
    use pixel color

  seed:
    random number

create BufferGeometry
set position attribute
set color attribute

create PointsMaterial with vertex colors
create THREE.Points
add to scene/camera

animation loop:
  get cycle time

  if cycle phase is FORMED:
    particles stay home

  if CRACKING:
    particles near crack shift slightly

  if BURSTING:
    particles lerp from home to burst

  if FLOATING:
    particles stay near burst plus sine/cos movement

  if RETURNING:
    particles lerp from burst back to home

  update position buffer
  mark needsUpdate true
Same Ideology As Your Current Work
Your previous text effect:
text pixels → particle home positions
hover → particles move to sigil positions
leave → particles return
This image effect:
image pixels → particle home positions
time cycle → particles move to burst positions
after delay → particles return
